==========================================================
PURPOSE
==========================================================

This document registers the official business decisions approved by the
project owner regarding the Quotation, Routing, Product and Project
Structure modules.

These decisions are final.

They must never be redesigned without explicit new authorization from the
project owner.

==========================================================
CONTEXT
==========================================================

These rules apply to the module chain responsible for generating a
Commercial Proposal, from customer need to production readiness:

Project → Product Items → Routing → Quotation → Commercial Proposal

==========================================================
DECISION 1 - PRODUCT DEFINITION
==========================================================

A product is not always fully defined at the moment of quotation.

Product definition may evolve gradually during the commercial process.

Engineering is part of the commercial process, not a separate phase.

==========================================================
DECISION 2 - ROUTING OWNERSHIP
==========================================================

The routing is linked to the specific project item, not to a generic
reusable product catalog entry.

Each project item has its own routing.

The routing defines the operations, resources and estimated times required
to manufacture that specific item.

==========================================================
DECISION 3 - QUOTATION COST SOURCE
==========================================================

The quotation calculates cost automatically from the routing.

Cost is never entered manually.

Cost is derived from:

Labor (resource cost x estimated time).

Raw materials consumed by the routing operations.

Productive resources used by the routing operations.

Consequence:

The routing must be technically complete (resources, materials, time)
before the quotation can calculate a valid total cost.

==========================================================
DECISION 4 - PRODUCT STRUCTURE (BOM)
==========================================================

Project items support infinite multi-level structure (multi-level Bill of
Materials).

In practice, structures rarely exceed three levels, but the system must
not impose a hard limit.

A project item may contain child items.

A child item may itself contain further child items, recursively.

==========================================================
DECISION 5 - COST AGGREGATION RULE
==========================================================

The cost of a parent item is the sum of the cost of its child items,
calculated recursively.

If an item has children:

Its cost equals the sum of all child item costs, recursively resolved to
the leaf level.

If an item has no children (leaf item):

Its cost comes directly from its own routing (labor + raw materials +
resources).

This aggregation must be calculated bottom-up, from leaf items to the root
item, and finally to the project total.

==========================================================
TECHNICAL CONSEQUENCE
==========================================================

The project items table must be self-referencing (parent_id / item_pai_id)
to support infinite hierarchy.

Cost aggregation must be resolved through a recursive query (recursive
CTE), not through manual summation logic scattered across the frontend.

This does not conflict with existing architecture principles. It is the
standard relational solution for hierarchical business structures.

==========================================================
IMPLEMENTATION ORDER (CONFIRMED)
==========================================================

Products → Routing → Quotation (consumes Routing) → Commercial Proposal

Routing must be functionally complete before Quotation cost calculation is
implemented.

